commentTextItems.html: on off and a repeat of the shot seals the victory

commentPostTextItems.html: So Sri Lanka are back in the series with their first win after a fine display with the bat on this rain-truncated day. But take nothing away from India's batsmen who did well with their 29 overs only to see the game reduced to 21 and Sri Lanka smooth home, thanks to a great knock from Jayasuriya and then Dilshan.

commentTextItems.html: on off and middle, swiped through long-off for two
left alone outside off
driven out through long-off for an easy four

commentPostTextItems.html: Four to win, and that's the 150

commentTextItems.html: stays over the wicket, the right hander driving the ball into his foot
down the track and doesn't get hold of a firm pull to midwicket
nipped back in from outside off, and turned in front of square

commentTextItems.html: shorter ball leaps over the outside edge down off
outside off cut off the back foot to the man at point
outside off, cut down into the covers, there's a run and a free hit next ball because of the overstep
angled on to leg, driven forward to mid-on
pulled round again but didn't quite time it
turned off the legs through the 45 for a forthright four
turned off the legs just in front of square

milestones.description: Jayasuriya has broken the record for most sixes (247) in ODIs, going past Shahid Afridi's 245

stories.title: Two shades of a plan
stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th ODI, Canberra
stories.summary: Tillakaratne Dilshan's match-winning 62 was more important in the match context than Rohit Sharma's unbeaten 70, which had the aesthetic value; while Rohit set up the contest, Dilshan ended it
stories.byline: Nagraj Gollapudi at the Manuka Oval

stories.title: Jayawardene hopes to build on opening momentum
stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th ODI, Canberra
stories.summary: On a day in which the weather played a major role, both rival captains credited the momentum handed to Sri Lanka's run chase by their openers as key to a first win in the CB Series
stories.byline: Nagraj Gollapudi at the Manuka Oval

stories.title: The lion roars, finally
stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th match, Canberra
stories.summary: Sri Lanka's first win of any significance on this tour couldn't have come at a better moment: it will lift the morale of a side that was seemed to be on the slide with one resounding defeat after another

stories.title: Learn the art of improvisation from the master

stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th match, Canberra
stories.summary: A 21-over match should have suited the reigning world Twenty20 champions India, but a revised-down total and some blistering early strikes from Sanath Jayasuriya lifted Sri Lanka to their first win of the CB Series

stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th ODI, Canberra
stories.summary: Tillakaratne Dilshan's match-winning 62 was more important in the match context than Rohit Sharma's unbeaten 70, which had the aesthetic value; while Rohit set up the contest, Dilshan ended it

stories.title: Jayawardene hopes to build on opening momentum
stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th ODI, Canberra
stories.summary: On a day in which the weather played a major role, both rival captains credited the momentum handed to Sri Lanka's run chase by their openers as key to a first win in the CB Series

stories.title: The lion roars, finally
stories.subTitle: India v Sri Lanka, CB Series, 5th match, Canberra
